    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Cultural and Educational Rights are guaranteed under Articles:","25-28","29-30","31-32","33-35","B","Easy","Cultural and Educational Rights are guaranteed under Articles 29 and 30 — right of minorities to conserve their language/culture and to establish educational institutions."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Under Article 20, a person accused of an offence cannot be punished for an act which was not an offence at the time of commission. This is called:","Double Jeopardy","Self-incrimination","Ex-post-facto law","None of these","C","Medium","Article 20(1) protects against ex-post-facto (retrospective) criminal legislation — a person cannot be convicted for an act that was not an offence when committed."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","'No person shall be prosecuted and punished for the same offence more than once' — this principle is:","Ex-post-facto","Self-incrimination","Double Jeopardy","None of these","C","Medium","Article 20(2) protects against double jeopardy — a person cannot be prosecuted and punished for the same offence more than once in a court of law."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Under which Article can Fundamental Rights be suspended during a National Emergency?","Article 352","Article 358","Article 359","Article 360","C","Medium","Article 359 allows the President to suspend enforcement of Fundamental Rights (except Articles 20 and 21) by order during a National Emergency. Article 358 suspends Article 19 automatically during National Emergency due to war."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Fundamental Rights CANNOT be suspended even during National Emergency?","Articles 14 and 15","Articles 19 and 21","Articles 20 and 21","Articles 32 and 226","C","Hard","Articles 20 and 21 cannot be suspended during a National Emergency (44th Amendment 1978). Article 20 protects against conviction and Article 21 protects right to life."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article provides that the State shall not deny to any person equality before the law?","Article 13","Article 14","Article 15","Article 16","B","Easy","Article 14 provides that the State shall not deny to any person equality before the law or equal protection of laws within India. It applies to all persons, not just citizens."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Article 19 of the Constitution guarantees which freedoms?","Freedom of Speech, Assembly, Association, Movement, Residence, Profession","Freedom of Religion, Conscience, Culture, Education","Freedom from Arrest, Detention, Double Jeopardy","Right to Equality, Education, Life","A","Easy","Article 19 guarantees 6 freedoms: (a) speech and expression, (b) peaceful assembly, (c) association, (d) movement throughout India, (e) residence/settlement, and (g) profession/occupation/trade/business."),

