    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Participation of workers in management of industries is directed under:","Article 43","Article 43A","Article 43B","Article 44","B","Medium","Article 43A (added by 42nd Amendment 1976) directs the State to take steps to ensure participation of workers in the management of undertakings and industries."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article provides for free and compulsory education for children as a DPSP (now modified)?","Article 44","Article 45","Article 46","Article 47","B","Medium","Originally Article 45 directed the State to provide free and compulsory education for children up to 14 years. After the 86th Amendment 2002, it was modified to provide early childhood care for children below 6 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Article 46 of the Constitution is related to:","Protection of monuments","Promotion of educational interests of SC/ST/OBC","Protection of environment","Uniform Civil Code","B","Easy","Article 46 directs the State to promote with special care the educational and economic interests of weaker sections especially Scheduled Castes and Scheduled Tribes."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article directs the State to maintain international peace and security?","Article 49","Article 50","Article 51","Article 52","C","Easy","Article 51 directs the State to promote international peace and security, maintain just and honourable relations between nations, and encourage settlement of disputes by arbitration."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Fundamental Duties in the Indian Constitution are contained in Article:","51","51A","52","53","B","Easy","Article 51A contains the Fundamental Duties. This article was inserted by the 42nd Constitutional Amendment (1976) after Swaran Singh Committee recommendations."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which is NOT a Fundamental Duty under Article 51A?","To abide by the Constitution","To protect and improve the natural environment","To pay taxes honestly","To safeguard public property","C","Easy","Paying taxes is not a Fundamental Duty under Article 51A. The 11 duties include: respecting Constitution/Flag, defending country, promoting harmony, protecting environment, developing scientific temper, etc."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Fundamental Duty 'to develop scientific temper, humanism and spirit of inquiry' is clause:","Article 51A(f)","Article 51A(h)","Article 51A(i)","Article 51A(j)","B","Hard","Article 51A(h) provides the duty to develop scientific temper, humanism, and the spirit of inquiry and reform."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article was added by the 86th Amendment 2002 as the 11th Fundamental Duty?","51A(j)","51A(k)","51A(l)","51A(m)","B","Hard","Article 51A(k) was added by the 86th Amendment 2002 — it is the duty of every parent or guardian to provide opportunities for education to child between 6-14 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","DPSPs were classified by Dr. B.R. Ambedkar into how many categories?","2","3","4","5","B","Hard","DPSPs are broadly classified into 3 categories: Gandhian (Articles 40, 43, 43B, 46, 47, 48), Socialistic (Articles 38, 39, 39A, 41, 42, 43A, 47), and Liberal-intellectual (Articles 44, 45, 48A, 49, 50, 51)."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 4: PRESIDENT & VICE PRESIDENT (141-175)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President of India is elected by:","Direct election by people","Members of Parliament only","Elected members of Parliament and State Assemblies","Members of all state legislatures","C","Easy","The President is elected by an Electoral College consisting of elected members of both Houses of Parliament and elected members of Legislative Assemblies of all states and UTs (Delhi, Puducherry, Jammu & Kashmir)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the election of the President of India?","Article 52","Article 53","Article 54","Article 55","C","Easy","Article 54 deals with the election of the President. The election is held in accordance with the system of proportional representation with single transferable vote."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum age to be elected as President of India is:","25 years","30 years","35 years","40 years","C","Easy","As per Article 58, a person must be a citizen of India, at least 35 years of age, and qualified for election as a member of the Lok Sabha to become President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The term of office of the President of India is:","4 years","5 years","6 years","Until age 65","B","Easy","Article 56 provides that the President holds office for a term of five years from the date of entering office. The President can be re-elected any number of times."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President of India can be removed by:","A motion passed by the Lok Sabha","Impeachment by Parliament","A resolution by both Houses jointly","The Supreme Court on petition","B","Easy","Article 61 provides for impeachment of the President. Impeachment charges can be initiated in either House and must be passed by 2/3 of total membership of that House, then by 2/3 of total membership of the other House."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Who administers the oath of office to the President of India?","Speaker of Lok Sabha","Prime Minister","Chief Justice of India","Vice President","C","Easy","Article 60 — The Chief Justice of India (or senior-most judge of the SC in his absence) administers the oath of office to the President of India."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The pardoning power of the President is contained in:","Article 70","Article 71","Article 72","Article 73","C","Easy","Article 72 empowers the President to grant pardons, reprieves, respites, and remissions of punishment to persons convicted of any offence."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the executive power of the Union?","Article 52","Article 53","Article 54","Article 55","B","Easy","Article 53 vests executive power of the Union in the President. The President exercises this power directly or through officers subordinate to him/her."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Disputes regarding election of President are adjudicated by:","Election Commission","Parliament","Supreme Court","High Court","C","Easy","Article 71 provides that all doubts and disputes in connection with the election of the President or VP shall be inquired into and decided by the Supreme Court."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President's address to Parliament at the beginning of the first session is mandated by:","Article 85","Article 86","Article 87","Article 88","C","Easy","Article 87 provides for special address by the President to both Houses assembled together at the commencement of the first session after each general election and first session of each year."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the Vice President of India?","Article 62","Article 63","Article 64","Article 65","B","Easy","Article 63 provides that there shall be a Vice President of India. The VP is elected by an electoral college of elected and nominated members of both Houses of Parliament."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Vice President of India is the ex-officio Chairman of:","Lok Sabha","Rajya Sabha","Planning Commission","Election Commission","B","Easy","Article 64 provides that the Vice President shall be ex-officio Chairman of the Council of States (Rajya Sabha)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Vice President is elected by:","Elected members of Parliament","Members of Parliament (both elected and nominated)","Electoral College same as President","State Assemblies","B","Medium","Article 66 provides that the VP is elected by members of both Houses of Parliament (including nominated members) in accordance with proportional representation with single transferable vote."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum age requirement for Vice President of India is:","25 years","30 years","35 years","40 years","C","Easy","To be eligible as Vice President, a person must be a citizen of India, at least 35 years of age, and qualified for election as a member of the Rajya Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The VP can be removed by a resolution passed by:","Lok Sabha with 2/3 majority","Rajya Sabha by majority + Lok Sabha agreement","Both Houses in joint sitting","Only Rajya Sabha","B","Hard","The VP can be removed by a resolution of the Rajya Sabha by a majority of its then members and agreed to by the Lok Sabha. There is no mention of specific majority required in Lok Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","When the President's office falls vacant, the VP acts as President. This is under which Article?","Article 63","Article 64","Article 65","Article 66","C","Easy","Article 65 provides that the Vice President shall act as President in the event of a vacancy or during President's absence. The VP then does not function as Chairman of Rajya Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article empowers the President to promulgate Ordinances when Parliament is not in session?","Article 121","Article 122","Article 123","Article 124","C","Easy","Article 123 empowers the President to promulgate Ordinances during recess of Parliament. An Ordinance has the same force as an Act of Parliament but must be approved within 6 weeks of Parliament reassembling."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The pocket veto is exercised by the President when he:","Refuses to give assent and returns the Bill","Does not return the Bill indefinitely","Sends the Bill to the Supreme Court","Refers the Bill to the States","B","Hard","The President can exercise a 'pocket veto' by keeping a bill pending indefinitely without action. However, in ordinary bills, Parliament can override this by re-passing the bill."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President can withhold assent from a Bill. Parliament can override the veto by:","Simple majority","2/3 majority","Absolute majority","The President cannot be overridden","C","Hard","If Parliament re-passes an ordinary bill (after the President returns it) by absolute majority and it is presented again, the President must give assent. The President cannot return a Money Bill."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article describes the qualifications for the office of President?","Article 56","Article 57","Article 58","Article 59","C","Easy","Article 58 lists the qualifications: must be a citizen of India, completed age 35, qualified for election as a member of Lok Sabha, and must not hold any office of profit."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President can seek the opinion of the Supreme Court on a question of law or fact under:","Article 141","Article 142","Article 143","Article 144","C","Easy","Article 143 grants advisory jurisdiction to the Supreme Court. The President can refer a question of law or fact of public importance to the SC for its opinion."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Financial Emergency is proclaimed by the President under which Article?","Article 352","Article 356","Article 360","Article 365","C","Easy","Article 360 empowers the President to proclaim a Financial Emergency if the financial stability or credit of India or any part thereof is threatened."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President's Rule in a State is imposed under:","Article 352","Article 356","Article 360","Article 365","B","Easy","Article 356 provides for imposition of President's Rule in a State if the President is satisfied that the constitutional machinery of that State has failed."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The National Emergency is proclaimed under which Article?","Article 350","Article 352","Article 354","Article 356","B","Easy","Article 352 provides for proclamation of a National Emergency on the grounds of war, external aggression, or armed rebellion. It was originally 'internal disturbance' changed to 'armed rebellion' by 44th Amendment."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Who was the first President of India?","Jawaharlal Nehru","Dr. S. Radhakrishnan","Dr. Rajendra Prasad","Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel","C","Easy","Dr. Rajendra Prasad was the first President of India (1950-1962). He was also the President of the Constituent Assembly. He served two terms."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 5: PM, COUNCIL OF MINISTERS & AG (176-200)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Council of Ministers is collectively responsible to:","President","Rajya Sabha","Lok Sabha","Both Houses of Parliament","C","Easy","Article 75(3) provides that the Council of Ministers shall be collectively responsible to the House of the People (Lok Sabha). This is the cornerstone of parliamentary democracy."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article provides for the appointment of the Prime Minister?","Article 74","Article 75","Article 76","Article 77","B","Easy","Article 75 provides that the Prime Minister shall be appointed by the President, and other ministers shall be appointed on the advice of the PM. The PM holds office during the pleasure of the President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The maximum size of the Council of Ministers (including PM) cannot exceed what percentage of Lok Sabha strength?","10%","15%","20%","25%","B","Easy","The 91st Constitutional Amendment (2003) added clause (1A) to Article 75 limiting the size of the Council of Ministers to not more than 15% of the total strength of the Lok Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Attorney General for India is appointed by the President under which Article?","Article 74","Article 75","Article 76","Article 77","C","Easy","Article 76 provides that the President shall appoint a person who is qualified to be appointed as a Judge of the Supreme Court as Attorney General for India."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Attorney General has the right to audience in:","Only Supreme Court","Supreme Court and High Courts","All courts in India","Only constitutional courts","C","Easy","The Attorney General has the right of audience in all courts throughout India. He appears on behalf of the Government of India in the Supreme Court."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The duties of the Prime Minister regarding information to the President are laid out in:","Article 75","Article 76","Article 77","Article 78","D","Easy","Article 78 provides that it shall be the duty of the PM to communicate to the President all decisions of the Council of Ministers relating to administration and proposals for legislation."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The concept of 'Cabinet' is mentioned in the Constitution of India in:","Article 74","Article 75","Article 352","The Constitution does not mention Cabinet","C","Hard","The word 'Cabinet' appears only once in the Constitution — in Article 352 (Emergency provision) where 'Cabinet' means the Prime Minister and other Cabinet Ministers. Article 74 mentions 'Council of Ministers'."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Council of Ministers assists and advises the President under:","Article 53","Article 73","Article 74","Article 75","C","Easy","Article 74(1) provides that there shall be a Council of Ministers with the PM at the head to aid and advise the President. The President shall act in accordance with such advice."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Who holds the office of Attorney General at the pleasure of which authority?","Prime Minister","Parliament","President","Supreme Court","C","Easy","The Attorney General holds office during the pleasure of the President and is not a member of the Cabinet or government but is the government's chief legal adviser."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Attorney General is entitled to take part in the proceedings of:","Only Lok Sabha","Only Rajya Sabha","Both Houses of Parliament and any joint sitting","Only Supreme Court","C","Medium","Article 88 provides that the Attorney General shall have the right of audience in all proceedings in Parliament. He can speak in both Houses and their joint sittings but cannot vote."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which article says that the President shall act in accordance with the advice of the Council of Ministers?","Article 73","Article 74","Article 75","Article 76","B","Easy","Article 74(1) provides that the President shall, in the exercise of his functions, act in accordance with the advice tendered by the Council of Ministers headed by the Prime Minister."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Under the 44th Amendment 1978, the President can:","Reject advice of Council of Ministers","Return advice for reconsideration once","Dissolve Parliament any time","Appoint PM without Council advice","B","Hard","Article 74(1) as amended by 44th Amendment allows the President to return the advice of Council of Ministers for reconsideration once. If the same advice is returned, the President shall act accordingly."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Solicitor General of India is:","The first law officer of India","The second law officer of India","The third law officer of India","Appointed under Article 76","B","Medium","The Attorney General is the first law officer of India. The Solicitor General is the second law officer, and Additional Solicitors General are below. The Solicitor General is not mentioned in the Constitution."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 6: PARLIAMENT (201-260)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Parliament of India consists of:","Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha","President, Lok Sabha and Rajya Sabha","Lok Sabha, Rajya Sabha and Supreme Court","President and Lok Sabha","B","Easy","Article 79 — Parliament of India consists of the President and two Houses: Council of States (Rajya Sabha) and House of the People (Lok Sabha)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The maximum strength of the Rajya Sabha is:","238","250","245","200","B","Easy","Article 80 provides that the Rajya Sabha shall consist of not more than 250 members — 238 elected by state/UT legislatures + 12 nominated by President for expertise in arts, science, literature, social service."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Rajya Sabha is a permanent House. How many members retire every two years?","1/2","1/3","1/4","None","B","Easy","The Rajya Sabha is a permanent body that cannot be dissolved. One-third of its members retire every two years after serving a 6-year term."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum age to become a member of the Rajya Sabha is:","21 years","25 years","30 years","35 years","C","Easy","A person must be at least 30 years of age to be elected to the Rajya Sabha (Article 84). For Lok Sabha membership, the minimum age is 25 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum age to become a member of the Lok Sabha is:","18 years","21 years","25 years","30 years","C","Easy","Article 84 provides that a person must be at least 25 years of age to be a member of the Lok Sabha. For Rajya Sabha, the minimum age is 30 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The current maximum strength of the Lok Sabha (after 104th Amendment) is:","545","543","550","552","C","Medium","After the 104th Constitutional Amendment (2019) which removed Anglo-Indian nominated seats, the maximum strength of Lok Sabha is 550 (530 from states + 20 from UTs). Currently there are 543 elected seats."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Speaker of the Lok Sabha is elected by:","President of India","Members of Lok Sabha","Members of both Houses","Prime Minister","B","Easy","Article 93 provides that the House of the People (Lok Sabha) shall, as soon as may be, choose two members to be respectively Speaker and Deputy Speaker."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Speaker of Lok Sabha vacates office when:","She/he is removed by a resolution of Lok Sabha","President removes the Speaker","Prime Minister advises removal","She/he completes 5-year term","A","Easy","Article 94 provides that the Speaker vacates office when: ceases to be member of LS, resigns, or is removed by a resolution of LS passed by effective majority (all members minus vacancies)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The quorum for a sitting of the Lok Sabha is:","50 members","55 members","100 members","1/10 of total membership","D","Medium","Article 100(3) provides that the quorum for a sitting of each House is one-tenth of its total membership. For Lok Sabha (543 members), the quorum is about 55 members."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A Money Bill can be introduced in:","Only Lok Sabha","Only Rajya Sabha","Either House","Both Houses simultaneously","A","Easy","Article 109 provides that a Money Bill shall not be introduced in the Rajya Sabha. It must be introduced only in the Lok Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Who certifies that a Bill is a Money Bill?","President","Prime Minister","Speaker of Lok Sabha","Rajya Sabha Chairman","C","Easy","Article 110(3) provides that if any question arises whether a Bill is a Money Bill or not, the decision of the Speaker of the House of the People (Lok Sabha) thereon shall be final."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Rajya Sabha can delay a Money Bill by how many days?","7 days","14 days","30 days","Rajya Sabha cannot amend a Money Bill","B","Easy","Article 109(2) provides that a Money Bill passed by Lok Sabha and sent to Rajya Sabha must be returned within 14 days. Rajya Sabha can only make recommendations (not amendments). Lok Sabha may accept or reject them."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A Joint Sitting of Parliament is called for resolving disagreement on:","Any Bill","Only Constitutional Amendment Bills","Ordinary Bills (excluding Money Bills and Constitutional Amendments)","Only Finance Bills","C","Medium","Article 108 provides for joint sitting of both Houses to resolve deadlock on ordinary Bills. It cannot be applied to Money Bills, Constitution Amendment Bills, or Financial Bills."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A joint sitting of Parliament is presided over by:","President","Vice President","Speaker of Lok Sabha","Prime Minister","C","Easy","Article 118(4) provides that a joint sitting of both Houses shall be presided over by the Speaker of the Lok Sabha or, in their absence, the Deputy Speaker or the Deputy Chairman of Rajya Sabha."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the Sessions of Parliament?","Article 83","Article 84","Article 85","Article 86","C","Easy","Article 85 provides that the President shall from time to time summon each House of Parliament. The gap between two sessions cannot exceed six months."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The maximum interval between two sessions of Parliament is:","3 months","6 months","9 months","1 year","B","Easy","Article 85 provides that Parliament shall be summoned at least twice a year. The gap between two sessions (prorogation of one and commencement of next) cannot exceed six months."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The concept of 'No Confidence Motion' is used to bring down the government. It is moved in:","Rajya Sabha","Lok Sabha","Both Houses simultaneously","Any House where it is first moved","B","Easy","A No Confidence Motion (Motion of No-Confidence) can only be moved and passed in the Lok Sabha. If passed by a simple majority, the government must resign."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Anti-defection provisions are contained in which Schedule?","Eighth Schedule","Ninth Schedule","Tenth Schedule","Eleventh Schedule","C","Easy","The Tenth Schedule (added by 52nd Amendment 1985) contains the Anti-Defection Law. A member who voluntarily gives up party membership or votes against party whip is liable for disqualification."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Speaker of Lok Sabha casts a vote only in:","All voting situations","Never","Tie situation (Casting Vote)","Every ordinary bill","C","Easy","The Speaker does not vote in the first instance but exercises a casting vote in the case of a tie. This is specified in Article 100(1)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with privileges of members of Parliament?","Article 103","Article 105","Article 107","Article 109","B","Easy","Article 105 deals with powers, privileges, and immunities of Parliament and its members. Members have freedom of speech in Parliament and are not liable for anything said in Parliament."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President addresses both Houses of Parliament together. This is called:","Budget Session","Zero Hour","Joint Address","Prorogation","C","Easy","Article 86(1) says the President may address either House or both Houses assembled together. Article 87 provides for the special address at the commencement of first session."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which special power does the Rajya Sabha have that the Lok Sabha does not?","Passing Money Bills","Declaring a national emergency","Passing resolution to create All India Services","Passing vote of no confidence","C","Hard","Under Article 312, the Rajya Sabha alone can pass a resolution (by 2/3 majority of its present and voting members) enabling Parliament to create new All India Services. Lok Sabha has no such power."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Parliament can legislate on State List subjects under which Article during President's Rule?","Article 249","Article 250","Article 251","Article 356 read with 357","D","Hard","Under Articles 356-357, during President's Rule Parliament can legislate on State List subjects for that State. Article 249 allows RS to pass resolution for national interest; Article 250 during National Emergency."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","An Ordinance promulgated by the President ceases to operate after how many weeks of Parliament reassembly?","4 weeks","6 weeks","8 weeks","12 weeks","B","Easy","Article 123(2) provides that an Ordinance promulgated by the President shall cease to operate at the expiration of six weeks from the reassembly of Parliament."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Budget (Annual Financial Statement) is presented to Parliament under which Article?","Article 110","Article 111","Article 112","Article 113","C","Easy","Article 112 provides that the President shall, in respect of every financial year, cause to be laid before both Houses the Annual Financial Statement (Budget)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which type of majority is required to pass a Constitutional Amendment Bill?","Simple majority","Absolute majority","Special majority (2/3 of members present and voting + majority of total membership)","Unanimous vote","C","Hard","Article 368 provides that a Constitutional Amendment Bill must be passed by each House by a special majority — two-thirds of members present and voting, which must also be a majority of the total membership of that House."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Deputy Chairman of the Rajya Sabha is elected by:","President","Vice President","Members of Rajya Sabha","Members of both Houses","C","Easy","Article 90 provides that the Rajya Sabha shall choose a member from among its own members to be Deputy Chairman. The Deputy Chairman vacates office if they cease to be members."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article provides that Parliament shall not discuss the conduct of a judge of the Supreme Court except on an address for removal?","Article 119","Article 121","Article 122","Article 124","B","Hard","Article 121 restricts discussion in Parliament on the conduct of any Judge of the SC or HC in the discharge of his duties, except on an address for the removal of the judge."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Rajya Sabha has special powers relating to which Article that enables Parliament to legislate on State matters in national interest?","Article 248","Article 249","Article 250","Article 251","B","Medium","Article 249 provides that if the Rajya Sabha passes a resolution by 2/3 majority that it is necessary in the national interest for Parliament to make laws on State List subjects, Parliament can legislate on those subjects for 1 year."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the special provisions as to Financial Bills?","Article 109","Article 110","Article 117","Article 118","C","Hard","Article 117 contains special provisions as to Financial Bills (Bills involving expenditure from Consolidated Fund). Such bills can only be introduced on recommendation of President."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 7: STATE LEGISLATURE & GOVERNOR (261-300)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Governor of a State is appointed by:","Chief Minister","State Legislature","President of India","Home Minister","C","Easy","Article 155 provides that the Governor of each State shall be appointed by the President by warrant under his hand and seal."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","What is the minimum age to become Governor of a State?","25 years","30 years","35 years","40 years","C","Easy","Article 157 provides that a person shall not be eligible for appointment as Governor unless he is a citizen of India and has completed the age of 35 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The term of office of a Governor is:","3 years","4 years","5 years","6 years","C","Easy","Article 156 provides that the Governor shall hold office for a term of five years from the date of entering office. The Governor serves at the pleasure of the President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The pardoning power of the Governor is contained in which Article?","Article 159","Article 160","Article 161","Article 162","C","Easy","Article 161 empowers the Governor to grant pardons, reprieves, respites, and remissions of punishment in respect of offences against laws relating to matters in State List."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Advocate General of a State is appointed under which Article?","Article 163","Article 164","Article 165","Article 166","C","Easy","Article 165 provides that the Governor of each State shall appoint a person who is qualified to be appointed as a judge of the High Court to be Advocate General for the State."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Advocate General holds office during the pleasure of:","Chief Minister","State Legislature","Governor","High Court Chief Justice","C","Easy","Article 165(2) provides that the Advocate General shall hold office during the pleasure of the Governor and shall receive such remuneration as the Governor may determine."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Advocate General has right of audience in:","Only High Court of the state","All courts in the state","All courts in India","Only Supreme Court","C","Medium","The Advocate General has the right of audience in all courts throughout India. He advises the State government on legal matters and represents the State in courts."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article requires the Governor to reserve a Bill for the consideration of the President?","Article 200","Article 201","Article 202","Article 203","B","Medium","Article 201 provides that when a Bill is reserved by the Governor for the consideration of the President, the President shall declare assent or withhold assent."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Chief Minister of a State is appointed by:","Election by State Legislature","President of India","Governor of the State","Vote of the Cabinet","C","Easy","Article 164 provides that the Chief Minister shall be appointed by the Governor. Other Ministers shall be appointed by the Governor on the advice of the Chief Minister."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the Council of Ministers at the State level?","Article 162","Article 163","Article 164","Article 165","C","Easy","Article 164 provides for a Council of Ministers headed by the Chief Minister to aid and advise the Governor. The Council is collectively responsible to the Legislative Assembly of the State."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The maximum strength of a State Legislative Assembly (Vidhan Sabha) is:","300 members","400 members","500 members","600 members","C","Easy","Article 170 provides that the Legislative Assembly of each State shall consist of not more than 500 members chosen by direct election from territorial constituencies."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum strength of a State Legislative Assembly is:","40 members","60 members","80 members","100 members","B","Easy","Article 170 provides that the minimum strength of a Vidhan Sabha is 60 members. However, Goa, Sikkim, Mizoram, and Nagaland are exceptions with fewer than 60 members due to special provisions."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article deals with the Composition of State Legislative Councils (Vidhan Parishad)?","Article 169","Article 170","Article 171","Article 172","C","Medium","Article 171 provides that the total membership of the Vidhan Parishad shall not exceed 1/3 of total membership of Vidhan Sabha, and shall in no case be less than 40 members."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President's Rule in a state can continue for a maximum period of:","6 months","1 year","2 years","3 years","D","Hard","President's Rule can be imposed initially for 6 months, extended with Parliamentary approval to 1 year, and further extended (in special circumstances) up to a maximum of 3 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article empowers the Governor to promulgate Ordinances when State Legislature is not in session?","Article 211","Article 212","Article 213","Article 214","C","Easy","Article 213 empowers the Governor to promulgate Ordinances when the State Legislature is not in session. A State Ordinance must be approved within 6 weeks of the Legislature reassembling."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The State Legislature can abolish or create a Legislative Council by:","Simple majority of State Legislature","Resolution of Vidhan Sabha + Parliament Act","Governor's order","President's order","B","Medium","Article 169 provides that Parliament may by law create or abolish a Vidhan Parishad (Legislative Council) if the Vidhan Sabha passes a resolution by special majority (2/3 of total membership)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Governor's address to the State Legislature is provided under:","Article 174","Article 175","Article 176","Article 177","C","Easy","Article 176 requires the Governor to address the State Legislature at the commencement of the first session after each general election and first session of each year."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Disqualification of members of State Legislature is decided by:","Governor","Chief Minister","Governor in consultation with EC","High Court","C","Medium","Under Article 192, if any question arises about disqualification of a member, the matter is referred to the Election Commission and the Governor acts in accordance with EC's opinion."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article confers powers on High Courts to issue writs for enforcement of rights other than Fundamental Rights?","Article 32","Article 136","Article 226","Article 227","C","Easy","Article 226 empowers High Courts to issue writs not only for enforcement of Fundamental Rights but also for 'any other purpose'. This is broader than Article 32 which is only for Fundamental Rights."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The duration of the State Legislative Assembly is:","3 years","4 years","5 years","6 years","C","Easy","Article 172 provides that every State Legislative Assembly shall continue for 5 years from the date appointed for its first sitting unless sooner dissolved."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","'Duties of Chief Minister as respects furnishing information to Governor etc.' is covered in:","Article 164","Article 166","Article 167","Article 168","C","Easy","Article 167 provides that the Chief Minister shall communicate to the Governor all decisions of the Council of Ministers, proposals for legislation, and furnish such information as the Governor calls for."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 8: EMERGENCY & AMENDMENTS (301-330)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A National Emergency under Article 352 can be proclaimed on which grounds?","War, External Aggression, Armed Rebellion","War and Economic Crisis","Political instability and war","Only External Aggression","A","Easy","Article 352 allows proclamation of National Emergency on grounds of war, external aggression, or armed rebellion. The 44th Amendment (1978) replaced 'internal disturbance' with 'armed rebellion'."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The first National Emergency in India was proclaimed in:","1962","1965","1971","1975","A","Easy","The first National Emergency was proclaimed in October 1962 during the Chinese invasion of India. The second was during the Pakistan war in 1971, and the third was the controversial 'internal disturbance' emergency of 1975."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A National Emergency must be approved by Parliament within:","1 month","2 months","3 months","6 months","A","Easy","A proclamation of National Emergency must be approved by both Houses of Parliament by special majority (2/3 of members present and voting + majority of total membership) within ONE month."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","During National Emergency, Lok Sabha can be extended for how long at a time?","1 year","2 years","3 years","Indefinitely","A","Medium","During a National Emergency, the normal 5-year term of Lok Sabha can be extended by Parliament one year at a time (not beyond 6 months after the emergency ceases to operate)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The President's Rule (Article 356) must be approved by Parliament within:","1 month","2 months","3 months","6 months","B","Easy","A proclamation of President's Rule must be approved by both Houses of Parliament within two months. It can be extended every six months up to a maximum of three years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Amendment to the Constitution provided that the National Emergency can be revoked by a simple majority in Lok Sabha?","42nd Amendment","44th Amendment","52nd Amendment","61st Amendment","B","Easy","The 44th Constitutional Amendment (1978) provided that if a resolution is passed by the Lok Sabha by a majority of its total membership disapproving the Emergency, the President must revoke it."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Financial Emergency declared under Article 360 has never been imposed in India so far. The approval must be obtained from Parliament within:","1 month","2 months","3 months","6 months","B","Medium","A proclamation of Financial Emergency must be approved by both Houses of Parliament within two months. There is no maximum period specified for Financial Emergency."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","During Financial Emergency, salaries of which officials can be reduced?","Only Central Government employees","All government employees including judges","Only MPs and MLAs","Only Ministers","B","Hard","During a Financial Emergency, the President can direct reduction of salaries of persons serving in the Union, State governments, and also directs that all Money Bills of States be reserved for Presidential assent. Salaries of SC and HC judges can also be reduced."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The procedure for amendment of the Constitution is provided in:","Article 365","Article 366","Article 367","Article 368","D","Easy","Article 368 provides the procedure for amendment of the Constitution. It distinguishes between amendments requiring simple majority, special majority, and special majority + State ratification."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which type of Constitutional provisions require ratification by at least half of the State Legislatures?","All amendments","Amendments affecting federal structure (election of President, SC, HCs, distribution of powers)","Amendments to Fundamental Rights","None of them","B","Hard","Amendments affecting federal structure — like election of President, extent of executive power of Union/States, SC and HC provisions, distribution of legislative powers — require ratification by not less than one-half of the State Legislatures."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The 42nd Amendment (1976) is also known as:","The Emergency Amendment","The Mini Constitution","The Secularism Amendment","The Justice Amendment","B","Easy","The 42nd Constitutional Amendment (1976) is called the 'Mini Constitution' as it brought sweeping changes including: adding Socialist, Secular, Integrity to Preamble; adding 10 FDs; strengthening DPSPs; changes in emergency provisions."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Amendment gave constitutional status to Panchayati Raj institutions?","72nd Amendment","73rd Amendment","74th Amendment","75th Amendment","B","Easy","The 73rd Constitutional Amendment (1992) gave constitutional status to Panchayati Raj institutions by adding Part IX (Articles 243-243O) and 11th Schedule with 29 subjects."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The 101st Constitutional Amendment is related to:","OBC Reservation","GST (Goods and Services Tax)","Right to Education","Electoral Reforms","B","Easy","The 101st Constitutional Amendment (2016) introduced the Goods and Services Tax (GST) by inserting Article 246A and amendments to Articles 269A and 279A, creating the GST Council."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Amendment introduced the 10% reservation for Economically Weaker Sections (EWS)?","101st Amendment","102nd Amendment","103rd Amendment","104th Amendment","C","Easy","The 103rd Constitutional Amendment (2019) introduced 10% reservation for Economically Weaker Sections (EWS) among the unreserved category in education and public employment."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The 104th Constitutional Amendment (2019) abolished:","Reservation for SC/ST","Nominated Anglo-Indian seats in Parliament and State Assemblies","Uniform Civil Code provision","Reservation for OBC","B","Easy","The 104th Constitutional Amendment (2019) abolished the provision for nomination of two Anglo-Indian members to Lok Sabha (Article 331) and similar provisions in State Assemblies."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Amendment inserted the Anti-Defection Schedule (10th Schedule)?","44th Amendment","52nd Amendment","61st Amendment","73rd Amendment","B","Easy","The 52nd Constitutional Amendment (1985) inserted the Tenth Schedule (Anti-Defection Law) which provides for disqualification of members of Parliament/State Legislatures on grounds of defection."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 9: MISC — CAG, FINANCE COMMISSION, FEDERALISM (331-350)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Comptroller and Auditor General (CAG) of India is appointed by:","Parliament","Prime Minister","President","Finance Minister","C","Easy","Article 148 provides that the CAG shall be appointed by the President. The CAG is the guardian of the public purse and audits all accounts of Union and State governments."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The CAG of India can be removed in the same manner as a Judge of:","District Court","High Court","Supreme Court","Election Commission","C","Easy","Article 148 provides that the CAG shall hold office until age 65 and can be removed only by the President on address by both Houses of Parliament by special majority — same as SC judge removal."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Finance Commission is constituted under which Article?","Article 278","Article 279","Article 280","Article 281","C","Easy","Article 280 provides for constitution of a Finance Commission. The President shall constitute a Finance Commission every 5 years to recommend distribution of taxes between Centre and States."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Election Commission of India is established under which Article?","Article 323","Article 324","Article 325","Article 326","B","Easy","Article 324 provides for the establishment of the Election Commission to superintend, direct, and control all elections to Parliament, State Legislatures, President, and Vice President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Chief Election Commissioner can be removed in the same manner as:","Comptroller and Auditor General","Judge of the Supreme Court","Governor","Attorney General","B","Easy","The Chief Election Commissioner can be removed only by the President on address by both Houses of Parliament by special majority — same manner as a Judge of the Supreme Court."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Article 262 deals with:","Distribution of tax revenues","Adjudication of disputes relating to waters of inter-state rivers","Election to Parliament","Appointment of CAG","B","Medium","Article 262 provides for adjudication of disputes relating to waters of inter-state rivers or river valleys. Parliament may by law exclude jurisdiction of Supreme Court in such disputes."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Inter-State Council is established under which Article?","Article 260","Article 261","Article 263","Article 264","C","Medium","Article 263 provides for an Inter-State Council to enquire into and advise upon disputes between states and to discuss subjects of common interest. It was established by Presidential Order in 1990."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Union Territory of Delhi has been given special status as 'National Capital Territory' by which Amendment?","65th Amendment","69th Amendment","73rd Amendment","76th Amendment","B","Easy","The 69th Constitutional Amendment (1991) gave Delhi the special status of National Capital Territory (NCT) by inserting Articles 239AA and 239AB."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Residuary powers of legislation in India rest with:","State Legislatures","Both Centre and States equally","Union Parliament","Courts to decide","C","Easy","Under Article 248, Parliament has exclusive power to make laws on any matter not enumerated in the Concurrent List or State List (residuary powers). This is borrowed from Canada."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Goods and Services Tax Council is established under which Article?","Article 246","Article 246A","Article 279","Article 279A","D","Medium","Article 279A (inserted by 101st Amendment 2016) provides for the constitution of a Goods and Services Tax Council to make recommendations on GST rates, exemptions, etc."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Schedule divides legislative subjects between Centre and States?","Fifth Schedule","Sixth Schedule","Seventh Schedule","Eighth Schedule","C","Easy","The Seventh Schedule (Article 246) contains three lists: Union List (97 subjects), State List (66 subjects), and Concurrent List (47 subjects) dividing legislative powers between Centre and States."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 10: SUPREME COURT (351-415)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Supreme Court of India was established on:","26 January 1950","15 August 1947","26 November 1949","28 January 1950","D","Easy","The Supreme Court of India came into being on 28 January 1950, two days after the Constitution came into force. It replaced the Federal Court of India and the Judicial Committee of the Privy Council."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article establishes the Supreme Court of India?","Article 121","Article 122","Article 124","Article 126","C","Easy","Article 124 establishes the Supreme Court of India. It provides for a Chief Justice and such number of other judges as Parliament may by law prescribe."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The current sanctioned strength of Supreme Court judges (including Chief Justice) is:","26","31","34","28","C","Easy","The Supreme Court (Number of Judges) Amendment Act 2019 increased the strength to 34 judges (including CJI). This was to reduce the backlog of cases."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A Judge of the Supreme Court holds office until the age of:","60 years","62 years","65 years","70 years","C","Easy","Article 124(2) provides that every Judge of the Supreme Court shall hold office until they attain the age of 65 years. (HC judges retire at 62 years.)"),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Who appoints judges of the Supreme Court?","Chief Justice of India","Parliament","President (on advice of CJI)","Prime Minister","C","Easy","Article 124(2) provides that every Judge of the Supreme Court shall be appointed by the President after consultation with such judges of the SC and HCs as the President may deem necessary. The CJI must be consulted for all appointments except for appointment of CJI."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The process of appointing SC and HC judges through the collegium system is known as:","Presidential Appointment System","Collegium System","NJAC System","Parliamentary Approval System","B","Easy","The collegium system (evolved through Second and Third Judges Cases 1993, 1998) gives primacy to the Chief Justice of India and senior judges in appointments and transfers of SC and HC judges."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A Judge of the Supreme Court can be removed by:","President on PM's advice","President on CJI's recommendation","President on address of Parliament by special majority","Supreme Court itself","C","Easy","Article 124(4) provides that a Judge of the SC may be removed by the President on address by both Houses of Parliament supported by a special majority (2/3 of members present and voting + majority of total membership)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","No judge of SC has ever been removed. The only judge against whom an impeachment motion was initiated was:","Justice V. Ramaswami","Justice K.G. Balakrishnan","Justice A.K. Ganguly","Justice H.L. Dattu","A","Hard","Justice V. Ramaswami (1991-1993) was the only SC judge against whom an impeachment motion was introduced in Parliament. The motion was not passed as the ruling party abstained from voting."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The seat of the Supreme Court is at:","Mumbai","Delhi","Kolkata","Chennai","B","Easy","Article 130 provides that the Supreme Court shall sit in Delhi or in such other place or places as the Chief Justice of India may, with the approval of the President, from time to time appoint."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Under which Article can the Supreme Court sit at a place other than Delhi?","Article 128","Article 129","Article 130","Article 131","C","Easy","Article 130 empowers the Chief Justice of India (with President's approval) to appoint other places for sittings of the Supreme Court besides Delhi."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Supreme Court is a Court of Record under:","Article 128","Article 129","Article 130","Article 131","B","Easy","Article 129 declares that the Supreme Court shall be a court of record with all the powers of such a court including the power to punish for contempt of itself."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article gives the Supreme Court original jurisdiction in disputes between the Government of India and one or more States?","Article 131","Article 132","Article 133","Article 134","A","Easy","Article 131 gives the SC exclusive original jurisdiction in any dispute between the Government of India and one or more States, or between States inter se. This does not apply to cases arising out of pre-Constitution treaties."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The appellate jurisdiction of the Supreme Court in constitutional matters is covered by:","Article 131","Article 132","Article 133","Article 134","B","Medium","Article 132 provides for appellate jurisdiction of the SC in appeals from HC judgments, decrees, or orders in civil, criminal, or other proceedings involving a substantial question of law as to interpretation of the Constitution."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Supreme Court has appellate jurisdiction in civil matters under:","Article 131","Article 132","Article 133","Article 134","C","Medium","Article 133 provides for appellate jurisdiction of the SC in appeals from HCs in civil matters, where the HC certifies that the case involves a substantial question of law of general importance."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The appellate jurisdiction of SC in criminal matters is covered by:","Article 132","Article 133","Article 134","Article 135","C","Medium","Article 134 provides for appellate jurisdiction of the SC in criminal matters. An appeal lies to the SC if HC has reversed an acquittal and sentenced the person to death, or has taken up a case from a subordinate court and sentenced to death."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Special Leave Petition (SLP) to the Supreme Court is under:","Article 132","Article 134","Article 136","Article 138","C","Easy","Article 136 grants the Supreme Court discretionary power to grant special leave to appeal from any judgment, decree, order, or sentence passed by any court or tribunal in India (except military tribunals)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Advisory Jurisdiction of the Supreme Court is exercised under:","Article 139","Article 141","Article 143","Article 145","C","Easy","Article 143 grants advisory jurisdiction to the SC. The President may refer a question of law or fact of public importance to the SC for its opinion. The SC's opinion is advisory, not binding."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Under which Article can the Supreme Court review its own judgments?","Article 135","Article 136","Article 137","Article 138","C","Easy","Article 137 provides that subject to any law made by Parliament, the Supreme Court shall have power to review any judgment pronounced or order made by it."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The power of the Supreme Court to enforce its decrees and orders is under:","Article 140","Article 141","Article 142","Article 143","C","Medium","Article 142 provides that the Supreme Court may make such orders as is necessary for doing complete justice in any cause or matter pending before it. These orders are enforceable throughout India."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Contempt of the Supreme Court can be punished under:","Article 127","Article 128","Article 129","Article 130","C","Easy","Article 129 declares the SC a court of record with all powers including the power to punish for contempt of itself. This contempt power extends to punishing contempt of High Courts also."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article provides that the civil and judicial authorities shall act in aid of the Supreme Court?","Article 141","Article 142","Article 143","Article 144","D","Medium","Article 144 provides that all authorities, civil and judicial, in the territory of India shall act in aid of the Supreme Court."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The jurisdiction of the Federal Court is transferred to the Supreme Court by:","Article 134","Article 135","Article 136","Article 137","B","Hard","Article 135 provides that the Supreme Court shall have jurisdiction and powers with respect to any matter to which the provisions of Article 133 or 134 do not apply, if that jurisdiction and those powers could have been exercised by the Federal Court under any law in force immediately before the commencement of the Constitution."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The SC can enlarge its jurisdiction under:","Article 136","Article 137","Article 138","Article 139","C","Hard","Article 138 provides that the SC shall have such further jurisdiction and powers with respect to any of the matters in the Union List as Parliament may by law confer."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Appointment of an acting Chief Justice of India when the CJI is absent is provided under:","Article 124","Article 125","Article 126","Article 127","C","Easy","Article 126 provides that when the office of CJI is vacant or the CJI is unable to perform duties, the President may appoint a Judge of the SC to perform duties of CJI."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Ad hoc judges of the Supreme Court can be appointed under:","Article 124","Article 126","Article 127","Article 128","C","Hard","Article 127 provides for appointment of ad hoc judges of the SC when there is no quorum of judges available, with the approval of the President, by the CJI from HC judges who are duly qualified."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Retired judges of the Supreme Court can be called upon to sit and act as SC judges under:","Article 127","Article 128","Article 129","Article 130","B","Hard","Article 128 provides that the CJI, with prior consent of the President, may at any time request a retired SC judge to sit and act as a judge of the SC. The retired judge is entitled to allowances as may be determined by the President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The transfer of cases from one HC to another or to the SC is provided under:","Article 136","Article 138","Article 139A","Article 141","C","Medium","Article 139A empowers the SC to transfer cases involving the same or substantially the same questions of law from High Courts to itself or from one HC to another HC."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article gives the Supreme Court writ jurisdiction (similar to Article 226 for HCs)?","Article 32","Article 136","Article 139","Article 141","C","Medium","Article 139 provides that Parliament may by law confer on the Supreme Court power to issue writs for any purpose other than those in Article 32. Article 32 itself is the writ jurisdiction of SC for FR enforcement."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The salaries of SC judges are charged to:","Consolidated Fund of India","Contingency Fund of India","Annual Budget approved by Parliament","Finance Commission grants","A","Easy","Article 125 provides that the salaries, allowances, privileges, and other service conditions of SC judges shall be as specified in the Second Schedule and shall be charged to the Consolidated Fund of India."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","After retirement, a permanent SC judge is prohibited from practicing in:","No court (can practice anywhere)","Only Supreme Court","All courts in India","Only High Courts","C","Medium","Article 124(7) provides that a permanent Judge of the Supreme Court shall not plead or act in any court or before any authority in India after retirement from office."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","In the Kesavananda Bharati case (1973), the Supreme Court held by a majority of:","9-4","7-6","11-2","13-0","B","Hard","In Kesavananda Bharati v. State of Kerala (1973), the SC ruled by a narrow majority of 7-6 that Parliament can amend any part of the Constitution but cannot alter its basic structure."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The doctrine of 'basic structure' means:","Parliament cannot amend the Constitution","The Preamble cannot be amended","Parliament can amend the Constitution but cannot alter its basic features","Only courts can amend the Constitution","C","Easy","The Basic Structure Doctrine (Kesavananda Bharati 1973) holds that while Parliament has wide amending power under Article 368, it cannot abrogate or damage the basic features of the Constitution."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which case held that 'Right to Privacy' is a Fundamental Right under Article 21?","Maneka Gandhi case","K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India","Vishaka v. State of Rajasthan","Francis Coralie Mullin case","B","Easy","In Justice K.S. Puttaswamy v. Union of India (2017), a 9-judge bench of SC unanimously held that Right to Privacy is a fundamental right under Article 21 of the Constitution."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The SC in Maneka Gandhi v. Union of India (1978) held that 'procedure established by law' in Article 21 must be:","Any procedure laid down by Parliament","Just, fair, and reasonable","Same as 'due process of law'","Approved by the President","B","Hard","The SC in Maneka Gandhi (1978) overruled A.K. Gopalan case and held that the procedure established by law under Article 21 must be just, fair, and reasonable — not arbitrary or oppressive. This greatly expanded the scope of Article 21."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","PIL (Public Interest Litigation) in India was pioneered by Justice:","Y.V. Chandrachud","A.N. Ray","P.N. Bhagwati","M.H. Beg","C","Medium","Justice P.N. Bhagwati (and Justice V.R. Krishna Iyer) were the pioneers of PIL (Public Interest Litigation) in India in the early 1980s, relaxing locus standi requirements."),

    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    # SECTION 11: HIGH COURTS (416-465)
    # ══════════════════════════════════════════════
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article establishes a High Court for each State?","Article 213","Article 214","Article 215","Article 216","B","Easy","Article 214 provides that there shall be a High Court for each State. However, Parliament can by law establish a common HC for two or more States (Article 231)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The High Court is a court of record under:","Article 214","Article 215","Article 216","Article 217","B","Easy","Article 215 declares that every High Court shall be a court of record and shall have all the powers of such a court including the power to punish for contempt of itself."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The judges of a High Court are appointed by:","Governor of the State","Chief Justice of India","President after consultation with CJI and Governor","Chief Minister on Governor's advice","C","Easy","Article 217 provides that every Judge of a HC shall be appointed by the President after consultation with the Chief Justice of India, the Governor of the State, and (for other judges) the Chief Justice of the HC."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The minimum qualification to be a HC judge is:","An Advocate for 5 years","An Advocate for 10 years","A District Judge for 7 years, or an Advocate for 10 years in HC","Any law graduate","C","Medium","Article 217(2) provides: A person is qualified for appointment as HC judge if they have been (a) a District Judge for at least 3 years (Article says 'on the rolls' is wrong — actually it's held 'judicial office' for 10 years), or (b) Advocate of HC for at least 10 years."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A Judge of the High Court holds office until the age of:","60 years","62 years","65 years","68 years","B","Easy","Article 217(1) provides that every Judge of a HC shall hold office until they attain the age of 62 years. (SC judges retire at 65 years.)"),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A judge of the High Court can be removed by:","Governor on CM's advice","President on address of Parliament by special majority","Chief Justice of India","High Court itself","B","Easy","A HC judge can be removed by the President on an address of each House of Parliament supported by special majority (2/3 of members present and voting + majority of total membership) — same procedure as SC judge removal."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The transfer of HC judges from one HC to another is done by:","President on advice of CJI","CJI independently","Governor concerned","Parliament by resolution","A","Easy","Article 222 provides that the President may, after consultation with the Chief Justice of India, transfer a Judge from one HC to another. The judge's consent is not required."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The salaries of HC judges are charged to:","Consolidated Fund of India","Consolidated Fund of the respective State","Annual State Budget","Finance Commission grants","B","Medium","Unlike SC judges whose salaries come from the Consolidated Fund of India, salaries of HC judges are charged to the Consolidated Fund of the respective State (Article 221)."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which Article gives High Courts wider writ jurisdiction compared to the Supreme Court?","Article 32","Article 136","Article 226","Article 227","C","Easy","Article 226 empowers HCs to issue writs not only for enforcement of Fundamental Rights (like Art. 32 for SC) but for 'any other purpose' as well — making HC's writ jurisdiction broader."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The power of superintendence of High Courts over all courts in the State is under:","Article 226","Article 227","Article 228","Article 229","B","Easy","Article 227 gives every HC the power of superintendence over all courts and tribunals throughout the territories in relation to which it exercises jurisdiction."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A case pending in a subordinate court involving a constitutional question can be withdrawn to HC under:","Article 226","Article 227","Article 228","Article 229","C","Medium","Article 228 provides that if the HC is satisfied that a case pending in a subordinate court involves a substantial question of law as to interpretation of the Constitution, it may withdraw the case and dispose of it."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Additional and acting judges of HC are appointed under:","Article 223","Article 224","Article 224A","Article 225","B","Medium","Article 224 provides for appointment of additional judges (for temporary increase in business) for a period not exceeding 2 years, and acting judges when a judge is absent or acting as Chief Justice."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Retired HC judges can be appointed as ad hoc judges under:","Article 224","Article 224A","Article 225","Article 226","B","Hard","Article 224A provides for appointment of a duly qualified retired judge of a HC as judge of that HC or another HC with the consent of the person and the President."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The jurisdiction of a HC can be extended to Union Territories under:","Article 228","Article 229","Article 230","Article 231","C","Medium","Article 230 provides that Parliament may by law extend the jurisdiction of a HC to, or exclude the jurisdiction of a HC from, any Union Territory."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","A common High Court for two or more States is established under:","Article 229","Article 230","Article 231","Article 232","C","Easy","Article 231 provides that Parliament may by law establish a common HC for two or more States or for two or more States and a Union Territory. (Example: Punjab and Haryana share a common HC at Chandigarh.)"),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The Officers and servants of the High Court are appointed by:","Governor","State Government","Chief Justice of HC","President","C","Medium","Article 229 provides that appointments of officers and servants of the HC shall be made by the Chief Justice of the HC or such other judge or officer of the HC as CJ may direct."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The jurisdiction of existing HCs (their original jurisdiction) is preserved by:","Article 225","Article 226","Article 227","Article 228","A","Hard","Article 225 provides that the jurisdiction of, and the law administered in, every existing HC shall be the same as immediately before the commencement of the Constitution, subject to the provisions of the Constitution."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Taking oath of HC judge is administered by:","Chief Justice of HC","Governor of the State","President of India","Chief Minister","B","Easy","Article 219 provides that every person appointed to be a Judge of a HC shall, before entering upon his office, make and subscribe before the Governor of the State an oath or affirmation according to the form set out for the purpose in the Third Schedule."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","After retirement, a permanent HC judge is prohibited from practicing in:","No prohibition","Only that HC","All HCs except Supreme Court","All courts in India","B","Medium","Article 220 provides that no person who has held office as a permanent judge of a HC shall plead or act in any court or before any authority in India except the SC and other HCs."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","Which is the oldest High Court in India?","Bombay HC","Madras HC","Calcutta HC","Allahabad HC","C","Easy","The Calcutta High Court is the oldest HC in India, established in 1862. The HCs of Bombay and Madras were also established in the same year 1862."),
    ("AP_HC","Indian_Polity","The High Court for the state of Andhra Pradesh (after bifurcation) is situated at:","Hyderabad","Amaravati","Vijayawada","Visakhapatnam","B","Medium","The Andhra Pradesh High Court is located at Amaravati (New Judicial Capital). After Telangana's formation in 2014, AP and Telangana initially shared the Hyderabad HC; AP got a separate HC at Amaravati."),
